excerpt: One of the most important Shinto sites in Japan, this complex has multiple shrines set amid forest.
detail_description: Kotai Jingu, also known as Ise Jingu Naiku or Inner Sanctuary, is a significant Shinto site in Japan. Nestled within a forest, this complex comprises multiple shrines that exude solemnity and high reverence. The shrine's architecture seamlessly blends with its natural surroundings, creating an atmosphere akin to a divine abode. Visitors can also witness the presence of a sacred horse that once received the emperor.
name: Kotai Jingu (Ise Jingu Naiku, Inner Sanctuary)

excerpt: Charming area with replica Edo-period wooden buildings housing craft stores & restaurants.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Ise, Okage Yokocho is a delightful destination that whisks visitors back to the charm of the Edo and Meiji periods. This enchanting area features replica wooden buildings that house an array of craft stores and restaurants, offering a taste of traditional Japanese culture. As you stroll through this recreated village, you'll discover teahouses and shops brimming with local delicacies like Japanese candies and folk crafts.
name: Okage Yokocho

excerpt: Ise is a coastal city in the central Mie Prefecture on Japan’s main island of Honshu. It’s known for Ise Jingu, a massive Shinto shrine encompassing 2 major shrines, the inner Naikū and outer Gekū. Between them are the Oharai Machi and Okage Yokocho alleys, lined with buildings reminiscent of Japan’s Edo and Meiji periods, now housing shops and restaurants. There are more than 100 smaller shrines in the city as well.
detail_description: Ise is a coastal city in Japan's Mie Prefecture, renowned for the grand Ise Jingu Shinto shrine complex, which includes the Naikū and Gekū shrines. The city features charming alleys like Oharai Machi and Okage Yokocho with Edo and Meiji period-style buildings housing various shops and eateries. Additionally, there are over 100 smaller shrines scattered throughout the area.
name: Ise

excerpt: This Shinto shrine with views of the ocean & "wedded rocks" has a vast array of frog sculptures.
detail_description: Nestled along the stunning coastline, Futamiokitama Shrine is a captivating Shinto shrine that offers breathtaking views of the ocean and the iconic 'wedded rocks,' known as Meoto Iwa. As you approach this serene site, you'll be greeted by an enchanting landscape adorned with frog sculptures and lined with majestic Japanese cypress trees. This picturesque journey leads to a place where pilgrims traditionally begin their ritual purification before heading to the revered Ise Jingu.
name: Futami Okitama Shrine

excerpt: Protected coastal area known for cliffs, caves & inlets, sheltering ospreys, turtles & cormorants.
detail_description: Ise-Shima National Park is a protected coastal area that encompasses cliffs, caves, and inlets, providing a habitat for ospreys, turtles, and cormorants. The park includes the revered Ise Shrine and stretches across the Ise Peninsula's coastline. It features a mix of natural beauty and human activity with boats on the horizon and pearl rafts dotting the seas.
name: Ise-Shima National Park

detail_description: Oharaimachi St is a traditional approach leading to Naiku, bustling with shops, food stalls, and restaurants that have been serving visitors for centuries. It takes a 15-minute bus ride from Geku-mae to Jingu Kaikan-mae and offers a vibrant atmosphere filled with local businesses catering to the steady stream of tourists.
name: Oharaimachi St

excerpt: Information about a centuries-old ritual held every 20 years, when the Jingu shrine is rebuilt.
detail_description: Nestled in the heart of Ise, the Sengukan Museum offers a fascinating glimpse into Japan's ancient traditions, particularly the Shikinen Sengu ritual. This centuries-old practice involves reconstructing the sacred Jingu shrine every 20 years, a tradition that dates back to 690 CE. The museum serves as a tribute to this remarkable event and showcases an impressive collection of artifacts related to Shikinen Sengu.
name: Sengukan Museum
address: 外宮域内, 前野-126-1 Toyokawacho, Ise, Mie 516-0042, Japan

detail_description: Geku, a Shinto shrine established over 1500 years ago, is dedicated to Toyouke-no-Omikami, the deity of food, housing, and clothing. The main sanctuary where the deity is enshrined can be reached after a five-minute walk from the entrance. One unique aspect of Geku is that its structures are reconstructed every twenty years as part of a sacred ritual.
name: Geku

excerpt: Aquarium where visitors can pet marine life & watch shows with dolphins, walruses & other animals.
detail_description: ISE Sea Paradise, located in Ise next to the sea, offers an interactive experience with a variety of marine animals. Visitors can enjoy playing catch with dolphins, taking photos with certain animals, and watching shows featuring dolphins, walruses, and other marine creatures. The aquarium is popular for its seal that sticks out its tongue and allows guests to see and touch various sea animals up close. Guests can also watch performances by cute sea lions and receive kisses blown by walruses.
name: ISE Sea Paradise

detail_description: Iseshi Station is a charming and well-maintained transportation hub located near the Geku Outer Shrine of Ise Jingu. It serves as a convenient gateway for tourists visiting the area, with easy access to the Kintetsu Railway connecting it to major cities like Nagoya, Osaka, and Kyoto. Nearby, visitors can find traditional Japanese inns such as Isegekusando Iseshinsen, known for its proximity to the station and natural hot spring baths.
name: Iseshi Station

detail_description: Hinjitsukan, located in Futami-cho, was originally constructed as a lodging facility for esteemed guests visiting Ise Jingu. Although it no longer operates as a guesthouse, it holds great historical significance as it once hosted members of the royal family and celebrities. The main building is an exemplary display of modern Japanese-style architecture from the Meiji to early Showa periods and has been designated an important cultural property by the government.
name: HINJITSUKAN

detail_description: Meoto Iwa, also known as the Wedded Rocks, is a renowned natural wonder in Japan located in the Ise Shima area. These two rocks stand in the sea and are connected by a thick straw rope, symbolizing a harmonious marriage and home safety. The area is considered sacred and features the Futami Okitama Shrine, dedicated to the god Sarutahiko for good luck, family safety, and traffic safety.
name: Meoto Iwa (Wedded Rocks)

detail_description: Akafuku Honten is a historic teahouse in Ise, known for its signature treat, Akafuku Mochi. This mochi is a rice cake topped with red bean paste and has a unique shape resembling the Isuzu River. The teahouse, established in 1707, was once popular among pilgrims visiting the area to pray at the Grand Ise Shrine.
name: Akafuku honten

excerpt: Surrounded by leafy trees & a river, this expansive, ancient complex is focused on 2 Shinto shrines.
detail_description: Toyouke Daijingu (Ise Jingu Geku, Outer Sanctuary) is a vast and ancient complex in Ise City, surrounded by lush trees and a river. It consists of two Shinto shrines, with the Toyoke Grand Shrine, also known as the Outer Shrine, being dedicated to Toyoke Omikami.
name: Toyouke Daijingu (Ise Jingu Geku, Outer Sanctuary)

excerpt: Spacious aquarium, founded in 1955, housing thousands of animals in 12 different themed zones.
detail_description: Toba Aquarium, established in 1955, is a spacious facility that is home to thousands of animals across 12 themed zones. It's one of the largest aquariums in Japan and offers a diverse range of creatures. Conveniently located just a 10-minute walk from Toba Station, it provides easy access for visitors. The aquarium features breeding exhibits that provide an immersive experience and unique shows for all ages to enjoy.
name: Toba Aquarium

excerpt: Famous for its cultured pearl aquaculture, this small island features a museum & ama diving shows.
detail_description: Mikimoto Pearl Island, located in Toba Bay, is renowned for its cultured pearl aquaculture and offers a range of attractions. The island features the Pearl Museum, showcasing antique jewelry made from natural pearls dating back to Roman times. Visitors can explore the process of pearl production and learn about the history of Kokichi Mikimoto, known as the King of Pearls, at the Kokichi Mikimoto Memorial Museum. Additionally, Pearl Plaza offers shops and restaurants for guests to enjoy.
name: Mikimoto Pearl Island

excerpt: Hot springs, folklore plays, kimono hire & shops at a theme park based on ancient Japanese culture.
detail_description: Ninja Kingdom Ise is a theme park that immerses visitors in the rich history and culture of ancient Japan. This unique destination offers a variety of attractions and activities, including hot springs, traditional folklore plays, kimono hire, and shops. At the heart of the park lies a meticulously recreated one-to-one scale Azuchi Castle, originally built by the renowned military commander Oda Nobunaga.
name: Ninja Kingdom Ise

excerpt: Busy udon shop with outdoor seating, known for soft, thick noodles served with locally brewed beer.
detail_description: Udon-ya Fukusuke is a bustling udon shop in Ise, offering outdoor seating and renowned for its soft, thick noodles paired with locally brewed beer. The restaurant's specialty lies in its Ise-style udon, featuring minimal broth and hearty noodles. Diners flock to Fukusuke for its delectable dipping sauce, meticulously crafted with natural soy sauce and bonito flakes to achieve a well-balanced and rich flavor profile.
name: Udon-ya Fukusuke
Jingu Kyu'ikirin Forest (Kyu'ikirin Forest of Ise-Jingu Grand Shrine)

detail_description: The Isuzu River, flowing gracefully near the Ise Grand Shrine, is a stunning destination for cherry blossom enthusiasts. Along the scenic route from Uji Bridge to Sarutahiko Shrine, visitors can admire vibrant cherry blossoms set against the backdrop of Mt. Asama and Mt. Kamiji. This picturesque area transforms into a magical wonderland during the Isuzu River Cherry Blossom Festival, celebrated when the blooms are at their peak.
name: Isuzu River

detail_description: The Ise-Shima Skyline is a picturesque 16.3 km toll road that links the towns of Ise and Toba. Known as The Driveway of Heaven, this route ascends to the summit of Mt. Asama, offering stunning panoramic views along its winding path. It provides an ideal opportunity to marvel at the beauty of the surrounding area.
name: Ise-Shima Skyline
Kodenchi (Site of Previous Sanctuary) (Geku Outer Shrine)

excerpt: Sequence of 4 wood shrines founded in the 9th century & dedicated to Shinto gods of the sun & moon.
detail_description: Tsukiyomi-no-miya Shrine, a collection of four wooden sanctuaries established in the 9th century, is dedicated to the Shinto deities representing the sun and moon. This tranquil haven serves as an ideal location for prayers before embarking on new endeavors. Despite its smaller size compared to Ise Shrine, Tsukiyomi-no-miya exudes a serene and invigorating atmosphere.
name: Tsukiyomi-no-miya Shrine

excerpt: Spain-inspired theme park featuring attractions such as rides, a museum, parades & live shows.
detail_description: Nestled in the picturesque Ise Shima region, Shima Spain Village is a captivating theme park that immerses visitors in the vibrant culture of Spain. Opened in 1994, this expansive resort combines an amusement park with a spa and accommodations, all wrapped up in charming Spanish-inspired architecture. The Parque de Espana offers an array of thrilling rides and engaging live shows, making it an ideal spot for families and adventure seekers alike.
name: Shima Spain Village
address: 字下山-952-4 Isobecho Sakazaki, Shima, Mie 517-0212, Japan

excerpt: Bayfront retreat offering a tranquil pedestrian promenade with sculptures & commemorative plaques.
detail_description: Futamiura Park is a serene bayfront retreat located in Ise City, offering a tranquil pedestrian promenade adorned with sculptures and commemorative plaques. The park features the famous couple's rock, where two stone statues face each other amidst the stretching beach and rapid water flow. This historical and cultural attraction is part of the expansive ISESHIMA National Park, which spans from Futamiura to KOWAURA Bay, encompassing semi-natural areas and coastal regions rich in biodiversity.
name: Futamiura Park
address: Japan, 〒519-0609 Mie, Ise, 二見町茶屋

detail_description: Tsukiyominomiya, a renowned Shinto shrine in Ise City, is devoted to the worship of moon deities. Despite its modest size, this shrine holds great significance in the region due to its association with the divine. As the sister shrine to the heavenly god, Tsukiyominomiya commands immense respect and admiration. The allure of this sacred place lies not only in its spiritual reputation but also in its tranquil ambiance.
name: Tsukiyominomiya

excerpt: Tranquil Buddhist temple, circa 1609, holding important paintings, sculptures & cultural artifacts.
detail_description: Kongosho-ji Temple, a serene Buddhist temple established in 1609, is renowned for its collection of significant paintings, sculptures, and cultural artifacts. The temple is famous for its stunning hydrangeas that bloom in June and is believed to bestow good health upon visitors. Nestled near the summit of Mt. Asakuma on the Ise-Shima Skyline, it offers a peaceful retreat where guests can enjoy green tea and engage with the welcoming resident monk.
name: Kongosho-ji Temple

excerpt: Shinto place of worship featuring an octagonal stone pillar that brings luck to those who touch it.
detail_description: Sarutahiko Jinja, a Shinto shrine in Uji, is a revered holy place recommended by Ota no Mikoto for Sarutahiko Okami. It features an auspicious octagonal stone pillar that bestows luck upon those who touch it. The shrine plays a pivotal role in Sikinensengu rituals, including the creation and presentation of sacred core pillars and wooden boxes. Positioned near Naiku's entrance are the Sarutahiko Shrine and Shoha Art Museum.
name: Sarutahiko Jinja

detail_description: Geku-sando, the front approach leading to Geku Outer Shrine, is a serene and sacred place in Ise City. The shrine's simplicity with gravel-covered walkways and wooden structures surrounded by a peaceful forest makes it fascinating. Along the approach from Iseshi Station to the Outer Shrine, there are souvenir shops, restaurants, and stylish cafes where visitors can leisurely stroll and choose souvenirs without much crowd.
name: Ise Jingu Geku-sando

detail_description: Yamatohime-no-miya Shrine, located within the Ise Jingu outer complex, offers a tranquil worship setting during the evening. Despite the absence of other worshipers, this relatively new Imperial Palace maintains a pristine appearance. Resembling a museum, it is encircled by a fence on its closed days. Accessing it may require parking in an empty space and embarking on a leisurely stroll along its lengthy approach.
name: Yamatohime-no-miya Shrine

detail_description: Mt. Asama, a lofty summit situated in Japan, stands as an impressive elevation that captivates with its grandeur. This majestic peak, renowned for its towering presence and awe-inspiring stature, is nestled amidst the captivating landscape of the region. Mt. Asama's colossal prominence renders it an iconic landmark in the area, enticing adventurers and nature enthusiasts alike to explore its remarkable trails and witness its breathtaking vistas.
name: Mt. Asama

detail_description: The Kazahinomi no Miya Bashi Bridge, also known as Isuzugawa Bashi, is located in front of the Kazahi-no-miya shrine in Ise Jingu. This bridge spans over the Shimaji-gawa river and joins with the Isuzu River downstream. Although smaller than Uji Bridge, it possesses its own unique beauty complemented by the scenic surroundings. The bridge offers a picturesque view and is a notable landmark in the area.
name: Ise Jingu Kazahinomi no Miya Bashi Bridge (Isuzugawa Bashi)

detail_description: The Kaguraden Hall (Naiku) is a sacred place within the Ise Shrine complex, surrounded by a majestic forest and towering trees. This grand temple offers a unique experience to visitors who seek spiritual connection. By partaking in the kagura prayer, one gains access to the inner sanctum where they can witness mesmerizing performances of live gagaku music and graceful shrine maiden dances. The serene ambiance allows individuals to immerse themselves in prayers, rituals, and other divine offerings.
name: Kaguraden Hall (Naiku)
address: Japan, 〒516-0023 Mie, Ise, Ujitachicho, 1, 皇大神宮内(伊勢神宮 内宮

detail_description: The Ise Furuichi Sangu-kaido Museum offers a glimpse into the rich history of the Furuichi neighborhood. Visitors can explore the sangu-kaido road that connected the Inner Shrine and Outer Shrine areas, learn about pilgrims' post-pilgrimage activities in the entertainment district, and discover the local performances of Ise Kabuki. The museum showcases a variety of exhibits curated by Mr.
name: Ise Furuichi Sangu-kaido Museum

detail_description: Toyouke Daijingu Betsugu Kazenomiya is a small shrine dedicated to the deity of wind, resembling the main sanctuary on a smaller scale. It is located along the approach to Taganomiya and enshrines Class Nagatsuhiko no Mikoto and Class leader Tobe Mikoto. The deity brings wind and rain, impacting crops significantly. Visitors note that the atmosphere at Kazenomiya feels different, possibly due to its association with the wind god.
name: Kazenomiya

detail_description: Yuki-no-Mikura-no-Kami is a Shinto shrine located within the inner precincts of the Imperial Palace in Japan. According to historical records, it was constructed before the 23rd year of Enryaku (804). The shrine, also known as Kotai Jingu, holds significance as it enshrines Yuki Mikura God, who is believed to be the guardian deity of Okura and associated with offerings made during various festivals.
name: Yuki-no-Mikura-no-Kami
address: Japan, 〒516-0023 Mie, Ise, Ujitachicho, 1, 皇大神宮内(伊勢神宮 内宮

detail_description: Matsuokannonji is a temple located in Osatsu-cho, a small fishing town in the Matoya Bay. The area is known for its ama huts where tourists can learn about the ancient tradition of ama fisherwomen diving for seafood. The temple is famous for warding off evil spirits and celebrates Kannon's birthday on the 18th of every month with a festival.
name: Matsuokannonji

detail_description: The Makonde Art Museum in Ise offers a variety of attractions for tourists looking for a weekend getaway. This museum showcases numerous rare exhibits that captivate visitors with their powerful and dynamic works. The second floor features artwork specifically geared towards adults, allowing them to appreciate the unique sense and talent behind these creations. For those interested, the museum also offers an hour-long viewing experience at an admission fee of 1000 yen.
name: Makonde Art Museum

detail_description: Taikoji Shukubo Hostel, located in Ise, is a Buddhist temple with shared bathroom facilities and air-conditioned rooms. The hostel provides free private parking for its guests. It is situated approximately 8 km away from the famous Ise Grand Shrine. Taikoji also offers a wind chime memorial service that brings a soothing ambiance when the wind blows. Additionally, visitors can park their cars near Ekominkan or in close proximity to the temple.
name: Choonzan Taiko Temple

detail_description: The Jingu Museum, established in 1993, serves as a memorial to commemorate the 61st Sikinensengu and preserve the historical legacy of Sengu for future generations. This museum exhibits a wide range of artistic creations including paintings, written works, and crafts crafted by renowned artists and skilled craftsmen from that era. The venue showcases various Jingu costumes and precious treasures alongside significant documents illustrating the enduring connection between the Japanese people and the Jingu throughout history.
name: Jingu Museum

detail_description: The Jingu Art Museum showcases a collection of donated artworks from various artists, which are currently on display. However, the true allure lies in the exquisite architecture and well-maintained gardens that surround the museum. The Agricultural Hall, Chokokan, and Sankan offer a combined ticket for 700 yen. Additionally, visitors can explore the Shosoin exhibition, featuring remarkable artifacts rarely seen before. The museum's front garden is adorned with blooming cherry blossoms throughout all seasons.
name: Jingu Art Museum

detail_description: Mishiodono Shrine, ranked 27th among the 30 companies under Kotai Jingu (Naiku), is one of the 125 Ise Jingu companies. It serves as the guardian deity for Mishiodono and Mishiodono, mentioned in the "Enryaku Ceremony Book" in 804. While being under Naiku's jurisdiction, Mishiodono Shrine also supplies hard salt to the outer shrine.
name: Mishiodono Shrine Mishiodono

detail_description: Otonashiyama Park offers a quick climb with many stairs from the free parking lot, providing access to an observation deck and ropeway ruins. The area used to be a leisure facility but now feels like a light trek up the mountain. Visitors can also see Meoto Iwa (Okitama Shrine) and enjoy views of Futami Ryokan town and the sea while hiking up the paved slope from Mt. Otonashi's entrance.
name: Otonashiyama Park

detail_description: While on the way to Uchinomiya Omiya recently, I chanced upon Former Toyomiyazaki Bunko, a historical site. Though the area was small, its cherry blossoms were truly picturesque. Amidst this serene scene, my attention was drawn to an inscription at the center of the space. I marveled at how such an exquisite character could be engraved even on a weathered surface that endures rain and wind.
name: Former Toyomiyazaki Bunko (School & Library)
